collections.name: CityIndex.TradingAPI
collections.description:
The first part of the CIAPI uses the software architecture style of Representational State Transfer (REST). This is one of the standard web service methods to communicate over the internet with remote servers.

The CIAPI RESTful implementation uses the Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTPS) for communication between our back-end and your trading solution (client UI application). Request / response calls initiated by the client UI application must follow a simplified RESTful pattern supporting GET and POST, and encoding data in JavaScript object notation (JSON).

Typically, requests for information such as: available markets, historical prices, and account history are exposed via HTTPS GET requests. Requests that change state such as: placing a trade or logging on are performed using HTTPS POST.

requests.name: GetPriceBarsBetweenDates
requests.description:
Get historic price bars for the specified market in OHLC (open, high, low, close) format, suitable for plotting 
in candlestick charts. Returns price bars in ascending order between fromTimestampUTC and toTimestampUTC. When there are no prices for a particular time period, no price bar is returned. Thus, it can appear that the array of price bars has gaps, i.e. the gap between the datetime of each price bar might not be equal to interval x span.

Sample Urls:

    /market/1234/barhistorybetween?interval=MINUTE&span=15&fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1400770798
    /market/735/barhistorybetween?interval=HOUR&span=1&fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1400785198&maxResults=10
    /market/1577/barhistorybetween?interval=DAY&span=1&fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1401476398

    param name="marketId" demoValue="71442">The marketId
    param name="interval" demoValue="MINUTE">The pricebar interval
    param name="span" demoValue="1">The number of each interval per pricebar
    param name="fromTimestampUTC" demoValue="1390402198">Start datetime
    param name="toTimestampUTC" demoValue="1400770198">End datetime
    param name="maxResults" demoValue="1000">The maximum number of pricebars to return. Default value is 1000
    param name="priceType" demoValue="MID">The price type being requested

requests.name: CancelOrder
requests.description:
Cancel the specified order - the order can be a resting entry order or an attached closing order to an open position.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment cancels the entry order with order ID 12345 for the trading account ABCD890.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: LogOn
requests.description:
Create a new session. This is how you "log on" to the CIAPI.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment logs in to your account using the example credentials of Username as "DM123456" and password as "openthedoor".

The AppKey required to use the CIAPI is sent to you once you have returned the signed terms and conditions of the CIAPI to our Partnerships team:

    (PartnershipServices[at]cityindex.com).

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiLogOnResponseDTO in JSON format.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment adds an attached if/done stop order to an existing entry order for the Wall Street CFD market. The existing entry order has the Order ID: 530539775
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: GetNewsDetail
requests.description:
Get the specific market news story matching the news headline ID in the parameter. The news headlines and headline IDs are returned from a ListNewsHeadlines call.

Return Value
GetNewsDetailResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment gets the news story for the headline with ID = 245177 from the dj news source. HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the market news story in JSON format (GetNewsDetailResponseDTO).

responses.text:
{"NewsDetail":{"Story":"    TAIPEI, May 23 (Reuters) - Taiwan will launch futures 
contracts for trading on the island of benchmark stock indices 
from the U.S. and India, a senior Taiwanese securities official 
said on Monday.  
    The Taiwan Futures Exchange is planning a futures contract 
for India's Nifty 50  .NSEI  by the end of this year at the 
earliest or the first half of 2017, Tsai Shih-chuan, vice 
president of the Taiwan Futures Exchange, told Reuters on the 
sidelines of an exchange event.     
    Tsai said the plans are to launch futures on the DJIA  .DJI  
and S&P 500  .SPX  at the end of 2017 at the earliest. 
    "The one for India will be faster...but the issue of time 
difference has to be resolved on (the contracts for) U.S. 
stocks," Tsai said.  
    The move is aimed at expanding Taiwan's futures market and 
attracting foreign investors, he said. 
    Last year, the island's futures exchange launched trading in 
Japan's TOPIX, so far the only foreign equity index futures 
traded in Taiwan.  
 
 (Reporting by Roger Tung; Writing by J.R. Wu; Editing by Sam 
Holmes) 
 ((jr.wu@thomsonreuters.com; +886 2 2500 4881; Reuters 
Messaging: jr.wu.thomsonreuters.com@reuters.net)) 
 
Keywords: TAIWAN FUTURES/  
     
","StoryId":423604,"Headline":"Taiwan to launch futures contracts for U.S, India benchmark indexes","PublishDate":"/Date(1463984685000)/"}}

requests.name: SearchWithTags
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. This search extends ListMarketSearch by optionally searching within a specified market tag and only returning matching markets from the specified tag. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the summarised MarketId and MarketName properties.

The market tag is optional and if not used, then this service call will behave the same as ListMarketSearch. The list of market tag IDs are provided in the table at Market Tag IDs.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" within the "Commodities" market tag (96), and returns the first ten results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the search results in JSON format (MarketInformationSearchWithTagsResponseDTO).

requests.name: GetActiveStopLimitOrder
requests.description:
Queries for an active stop limit order with a specified order ID. It returns a null value if the order doesn't exist, or is not an active stop limit order.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call the HTTP service ListActiveStopLimitOrders for the initial data to display in the grid, and call this URI when you receive updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format. For a more comprehensive order response, see the HTTP service GetOrder.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment queries the active order with ID = 123456. HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the order query result in JSON format (GetActiveStopLimitOrderResponseDTO).

requests.description:
Get historic price ticks for the specified market.  
Returns price ticks in ascending order before timestampUTC.
The length of time that elapses between each tick is usually different.

Sample Urls:

    /market/1234/tickhistorybefore?toTimestampUTC=1400770798&priceType=ASK
    /market/735/tickhistorybefore?toTimestampUTC=1400785198&maxResults=10
    /market/1577/tickhistorybefore?toTimestampUTC=1401476398&priceType=BID

    param name="marketId" demoValue="71442">The marketId
    param name="maxResults" demoValue="1000">The maximum number of price ticks to return. Default value is 1000
    param name="toTimestampUTC" demoValue="1400770198">End datetime
    param name="priceType" demoValue="MID">The price type being requested

requests.name: ListStopLimitOrderHistory
requests.description:
Queries the stop / limit order history for a specified trading account. The result set includes only orders that were originally stop / limit orders that currently have one of the following statuses (3 - Open, 4 - Cancelled, 5 - Rejected, 9 - Closed, 10 - Red Card). There is currently no corresponding GetStopLimitOrderHistory (as with ListActiveStopLimitOrders).
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

requests.name: ListMarketSearch GTS
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. The search can be performed by market code and/or market name, and can include CFDs and Spread Bet markets. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the summarised MarketId and MarketName properties.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the first ten search results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the search results in JSON format (ListMarketSearchResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListMarketInformationSearch GTS
requests.description:
Returns market information for the markets that meet the search criteria. The search can be performed by market code and/or market name, and can include CFDs and Spread Bet markets.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the market information for the first ten.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the market information for the search results (ListMarketInformationResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListSpreadMarkets
requests.description:
Returns a list of Spread Betting markets filtered by market name and/or market code. Leave the market name and code parameters empty to return all markets available to the User.

Return Value
ListSpreadMarketsResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment retrieves the list of Spread Bet markets matching the following search criteria: market name contains "Gold", a maximum of 20 results returned, and use the short form of the market name.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the market list information in JSON format (ListSpreadMarketsResponseDTO).

requests.name: Trade BUY
requests.description:
This service is used for two functions:
Place an opening trade on a particular market. Do not set any order ID fields when requesting a new trade, the platform will generate them. The trade request may contain conditional if/done attached stop loss and limit closing orders.
Close an open position. In this case, set the Close property with the Order ID of the opening trade.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment places a trade to buy 1 contract of the Wall Street CFD market at 17912.8.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: Trade SELL
requests.description:
This service is used for two functions:
Place an opening trade on a particular market. Do not set any order ID fields when requesting a new trade, the platform will generate them. The trade request may contain conditional if/done attached stop loss and limit closing orders.
Close an open position. In this case, set the Close property with the Order ID of the opening trade.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment places a trade to buy 1 contract of the Wall Street CFD market at 17912.8.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: GetOrdersByReference
requests.description:
Queries for an orders by a specific order reference.
The current implementation returns orders with any status.
Should be used only for FIX API. Can return unexpected results while using with other purposes.

requests.name: ListTradeHistory
requests.description:
Queries the trade history for a specified trading account. The result set will contain orders with a status of (3 - Open, 9 - Closed), and includes orders that were a trade / stop / limit order. There's currently no corresponding GetTradeHistory (as with ListOpenPositions).
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

requests.description:

Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the summarised MarketId and MarketName properties.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the first ten search results.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the search results in JSON format (ListMarketSearchResponseDTO).

requests.name: SearchWithTags GTS
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. This search extends ListMarketSearch by optionally searching within a specified market tag and only returning matching markets from the specified tag. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the summarised MarketId and MarketName properties.

The market tag is optional and if not used, then this service call will behave the same as ListMarketSearch. The list of market tag IDs are provided in the table at Market Tag IDs.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" within the "Commodities" market tag (96), and returns the first ten results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the search results in JSON format (MarketInformationSearchWithTagsResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListActiveStopLimitOrders
requests.description:
Queries for a specified trading account's active stop / limit orders.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call this for the initial data to display in the grid, then call the HTTP service GetActiveStopLimitOrder when you get updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format.
 
Notes on Parameters
ClientAccountId - this can be passed in order to retrieve all information on all trading accounts for which it is the parent. TradingAccountId - this can be passed to retrieve information specific to a certain trading account (the child of ClientAccount).
If neither ClientAccountId nor TradingAccountId is passed, then the information returned by default from the API is ClientAccount.

requests.name: Order BUY
requests.description:
This service is used to place a new resting entry order on a particular market. Do not set any order ID fields when requesting a new order, the platform will generate them.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment places an entry Limit order to buy 1 contract of the Wall Street CFD market at 19,000.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: ListMarketSearchPaginated GTS
requests.description:
Returns a markets page containing a list of markets that meet the search criteria. The search can be performed by market code and/or market name, and can include CFDs and Spread Bet markets. This method differs from ListMarketSearch in that the returned results are paginated.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the first 20 results. The results are shown as 5 markets per page starting from page 1.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the paginated search results in JSON format (ListMarketSearchPaginatedResponseDTO).

requests.name: GetOpenPosition
requests.description:
Queries for a trade / open position with a specified order ID. It returns a null value if the order doesn't exist, or is not a trade / open position.
This URI is intended to support a grid in a UI. One usage pattern is to subscribe to streaming orders, call the HTTP service ListOpenPositions for the initial data to display in the grid, and call this URI when you receive updates on the order stream to get the updated data in this format. For a more comprehensive order response, see the HTTP service GetOrder.

Return Value
GetOpenPositionResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment queries the open position with ID = 123456. HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the open position query result in JSON format (GetOpenPositionResponseDTO).

responses.name: ListMarketInformationSearchResponseDTO

requests.name: ListMarketSearchPaginated
requests.description:
Returns a markets page containing a list of markets that meet the search criteria. The search can be performed by market code and/or market name, and can include CFDs and Spread Bet markets. This method differs from ListMarketSearch in that the returned results are paginated.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" and returns the first 20 results. The results are shown as 5 markets per page starting from page 1.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the paginated search results in JSON format (ListMarketSearchPaginatedResponseDTO).

requests.name: GetLatestPriceTicks
requests.description:
Get historic price ticks for the specified market.  
Returns price ticks in ascending order up to the current time.
The length of time that elapses between each tick is usually different.

Sampe url:

    /market/1234/tickhistory?priceTicks=180&priceType=ASK
    /market/735/tickhistory?priceTicks=240
    /market/1577/tickhistory?priceTicks=10&priceType=BID

    param name="marketId" demoValue="71442">The marketId
    param name="priceTicks" demoValue="10">The total number of price ticks to return
    param name="priceType" demoValue="MID">The price type being requested

requests.name: GetPriceTicksBetweenDates
requests.description:
Get historic price ticks for the specified market.  
Returns price ticks in ascending order after fromTimestampUTC and before toTimestampUTC.
The length of time that elapses between each tick is usually different.

Sample Urls:

    /market/1234/tickhistorybetween?fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1400770798&priceType=ASK
    /market/735/tickhistorybetween?fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1400785198&maxResults=10
    /market/1577/tickhistorybetween?fromTimestampUTC=1390402198&toTimestampUTC=1401476398&priceType=BID

    param name="marketId" demoValue="71442">The marketId
    param name="maxResults" demoValue="1000">The maximum number of price ticks to return. Default value is 1000
    param name="fromTimestampUTC" demoValue="1390402198">Start datetime
    param name="toTimestampUTC" demoValue="1400770198">End datetime
    param name="priceType" demoValue="MID">The price type being requested

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the market list information in JSON format (AccountInformationResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListMarketInformation
requests.description:
Retrieve the Market Information for the markets in the specified list of market IDs.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment requests the market information for the markets in the following list:
UK 100 DFT (400616113)
UK 100 CFD (99500)
GBP/USD DFT (400616150)
EUR/USD CFD (154290)
 
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: FullSearchWithTags GTS
requests.description:
Returns a list of markets that meet the search criteria. This search extends ListMarketInformationSearch by optionally searching within a specified market tag and only returning matching markets from the specified tag. Leave the query string empty to return all markets available to the user. The results contain the full ApiMarketInformationDTO.

The market tag is optional and if not used, then this service call will behave the same as ListMarketInformationSearch. The list of market tag IDs are provided in the table at Market Tag IDs.

Note: when searching for currency markets by name enter the format as "USD JPY" or "GBP USD". Do not use the "/" in the name of the currency pair.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment searches for markets with names matching the query string "Gold" within the "Commodities" market tag (96), and returns the first ten results. The full market information is returned for all search results.
HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing market information for the search results in JSON format (FullMarketInformationSearchWithTagsResponseDTO).

requests.name: GetMarketInformation
requests.description:
Get Market Information for the single specified market supplied in the parameter.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment retrieves the market information for Gold DFT, which has the ID 400616377. HTTP GET does not use the body. Parameters should be added in the query string.

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body containing the market information for the requested market in JSON format (AccountInformationResponseDTO).

requests.name: ListNewsHeadlines
requests.description:
Get a list of current news headlines matching the request parameters. The list of news headlines can be filtered by various criteria such as market, or geographic region.

Return Value
ListNewsHeadlinesResponseDTO
 
Example

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment requests the most recent 10 news headlines from the dj source for the Wall Street CFD market (ID: 99498).
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ListNewsHeadlinesResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: GetLatestPriceBars
requests.description:
Get historic price bars for the specified market in OHLC (open, high, low, close) format, suitable for plotting 
in candlestick charts. Returns price bars in ascending order up to the current time. When there are no prices for 
a particular time period, no price bar is returned. Thus, it can appear that the array of price bars 
has gaps, i.e. the gap between the datetime of each price bar might not be equal to interval x span.

Sample Urls:

    /market/1234/barhistory?interval=MINUTE&span=15&pricebars=180
    /market/735/barhistory?interval=HOUR&span=1&pricebars=240
    /market/1577/barhistory?interval=DAY&span=1&pricebars=10

    param name="marketId" demoValue="71442">The marketId
    param name="interval" demoValue="MINUTE">The pricebar interval
    param name="span" demoValue="1">The number of each interval per pricebar
    param name="priceBars" demoValue="15">The total number of pricebars to return
    param name="priceType" demoValue="MID">The price type being requested

requests.description:
Change a user's password.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment changes the DM123456 account password from "allsystemsgo" to "openthedoor".

Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiSaveAccountInformationResponseDTO in JSON format.

requests.name: UpdateTrade
requests.description:
This service is used for two functions:
Add a new closing stop loss and/or take profit limit order attached to an open position.
Modify the details for existing closing orders attached to an open position.

The following request to the Live CIAPI environment adds a stop loss order to an open trade in the Wall Street CFD market.
Note: the authentication UserName and Session token are not shown in the example for the purposes of clarity, but they are required in the actual query string.

A successful request results in an HTTP 200 code in the response header, and the response body is the ApiTradeOrderResponseDTO in JSON format.

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema"><soap:Body><SearchMessageTranslationsResponse xmlns="http://cityindex.co.uk/MessageTranslation"><SearchMessageTranslationsResult><msg_tr><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternCommonDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. If both conditions are met, the doji is identified.</v><desc /><id>983</id></msg_tr><msg_tr><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternDragonflyDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. Third, the open and close values are both tested to equal the high value. If these conditions are met, the dragonfly is identified.</v><desc /><id>987</id></msg_tr><msg_tr><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternGravestoneDoji_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or less-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be greater-than or equal-to the second parameter. Third, the open and close values are both tested to equal the low value. If these conditions are met, the gravestone is identified.</v><desc /><id>991</id></msg_tr><msg_tr><app_id>1</app_id><culture>69</culture><k>PatternHammer_calculation</k><v>First, the body height of the candle is tested to be equal-to or greater-than the first parameter. Second, the total height is tested to be at least twice the height of the body of the candle. Third, the close value is tested to equal the high value. This tool allows you to update the look and feel of the platform by changing the colours displayed. \n

You can change the colours by performing the following steps:\n

1. Select a row that contains a colour that you want to update\n

When you do this, you will see a description of what elements relate to the colour.\n

2. Use the "New Colour Value" column to update the colour\n

In the "New Colour" column you are provided with a colour picker and a textbox containing the code for the associated colour.\n

Click on the colour picker and select the colour you prefer.\n

Where there are 2 colours, this simply means that the update relates to a gradient colour.\n

3. Click the "Apply" button to apply your changes to your current session.\n

This will update the colours of the IFE in your current session and refresh your layout to the default. If using a layout other than the default please ensure that you have saved your changes.\n

4. Click the "Save & Close" button to save your changes for future sessions.\n

If you do not click this whilst editing the CSS, then all changes will be lost.\n

5. Click the "Close" button to close the CSS window\n

You will be prompted to save any changes that you have made to ensure that you do not lose any updates accidentally. \n

6. If you want to revert back to the default colours for the platform, click the "Restore Default Values" button.\n

This will revert the site back to the default colours. \n

Help: If you wish to see this information again, simply click the "Help" button. </v><desc>Text
